The Senate is set to put an end to the claims and counter-claims on the fuel subsidy by oil marketers, Daily Trust reports. This followed the presentation and laying of the report of the committee on petroleum (downstream) chaired by Sen Kabiru Garba Marafa (APC, Zamfara), on the floor of the Senate yesterday. The report, titled Promissory Note and Bond Issuance for 19 Oil Marketers’ Outstanding Claims,’ made some far-reaching recommendations on how to resolve the logjam, it was learnt. The Senate had in July last year approved the payment of N348 billion as outstanding subsidy claims to 74 oil marketers. Consequently, some payments had been made to the marketers. In December last year, the oil marketers confirmed that they had received N236.99billon being the first tranche of outstanding subsidy debts promised to be paid them by the federal government. The marketers, made up of Major Oil Marketers Association of Nigeria (MOMAN) Depot and Petroleum Products Marketers Association (DAPPMAN) and Independent Petroleum Products Importers (IPPI) had threatened to shut down fuel depots due to the outstanding subsidy arrears owed by the government. Pay outstanding fuel subsidy claims, marketers plead with FG FG pays oil marketers, freezes interest on loan page 19 new Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin